:::summary
Brigham Young (1801–1877) was the second President and Prophet of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, the primary architect of the Mormon pioneer migration to Utah, and one of the most remarkable leaders in American religious and frontier history. A carpenter and craftsman before his conversion to the restored Gospel, Young became an apostle, led the quorum of the Twelve Apostles following Joseph Smith's martyrdom, and guided tens of thousands of Saints across the wilderness to the Salt Lake Valley — where he built a thriving community of settlements that eventually became the state of Utah. He was simultaneously a theologian, an administrator of extraordinary practical genius, a colonizer, a territorial governor, and a father of fifty-six children.
:::

